================================================================================
        GIT COMMANDS - SAMPLE EXAMPLES FOR BEGINNERS
================================================================================

A complete guide with practical examples to help beginners understand Git easily.

================================================================================
EXAMPLE 1: YOUR FIRST PROJECT (LOCAL) (DATE 26/06)
================================================================================

Scenario: Creating a project from scratch and saving your work

Commands:
---------
# Step 1: Create a new folder and initialize Git
mkdir my-project
cd my-project
git init

# Step 2: Create a file
echo "Hello World" > hello.txt

# Step 3: Check what changed
git status
# Output: "hello.txt" is untracked

# Step 4: Stage the file (prepare it for saving)
git add hello.txt

# Step 5: Save it with a message (commit)
git commit -m "Add hello.txt file"

# Step 6: See your history
git log
# Shows: commit message, author, date

What They Learn:
----------------
The basic save cycle (create → add → commit)


================================================================================
EXAMPLE 2: MAKING CHANGES & SEEING DIFFERENCES (DATE 26/06)
================================================================================

Scenario: Modifying a file and reviewing what changed

Commands:
---------
# File originally has: "Hello World"
# You modify it to: "Hello World! Welcome"

# See what changed
git diff
# Output shows:
# - Hello World
# + Hello World! Welcome

# Stage and commit the change (optional)
git add hello.txt
git commit -m "Update greeting message"

What They Learn:
----------------
Tracking changes and reviewing before committing


================================================================================
EXAMPLE 3: WORKING WITH BRANCHES (DATE 26/06)
================================================================================

Scenario: Adding a new feature without affecting the main code

Commands:
---------
# You're on "main" branch (main version)
git branch
# Output: * main

# Create a new branch for a feature
git branch feature/add-colors
git checkout feature/add-colors
# OR in one command: git checkout -b feature/add-colors

# Now you're in the new branch
git branch
# Output:
#   main
# * feature/add-colors

# Make changes and commit in this branch
echo "Adding color support" > feature.txt
git add feature.txt
git commit -m "Add color feature"

# Switch back to main (untouched)
git checkout main
# feature.txt doesn't exist here!

# Go back to your feature branch
git checkout feature/add-colors
# feature.txt is back!

What They Learn:
----------------
Branches keep different work separate

================================================================================
EXAMPLE 7: WORKING WITH REMOTE (GITHUB) (DATE 26/06)
================================================================================

Scenario: Sharing code online

Commands:
---------
# Step 1: Clone (download) a project from GitHub
git clone https://github.com/user/project.git
cd project

# Step 2: Make changes
echo "New feature" > new-file.txt
git add new-file.txt
git commit -m "Add new feature"

# Step 3: Upload changes back to GitHub
git push origin main

# Step 4: Download updates from GitHub
git pull origin main

What They Learn:
----------------
Collaborating with others online


================================================================================
EXAMPLE 8: REAL PROJECT WORKFLOW (COMPLETE) (DATE 26/06)
================================================================================

Scenario: A typical day working on a project

Commands:
---------
# Morning: Start with latest code
git pull origin main

# Work on a feature
git checkout -b feature/user-login
echo "Login functionality" > feature.txt
git add feature.txt
git commit -m "Add login form"

# Update feature based on review
echo "Login with validation" > feature.txt
git add feature.txt
git commit -m "Add form validation"

# Send to GitHub
git push origin feature/user-login

# Cleanup (optional)
git branch -d feature/user-login

================================================================================
EXAMPLE 4: MERGING BRANCHES
================================================================================

Scenario: Your feature is done, now merge it back to main

Commands:
---------
# You're in feature/add-colors branch
git commit -m "Complete color feature"

# Switch to main
git checkout main

# Merge the feature branch into main
git merge feature/add-colors
# Output: "Merge made by..."

# Now main has all changes from feature branch
git log
# Shows both commits

# Delete the feature branch (cleanup)
git branch -d feature/add-colors

What They Learn:
----------------
Combining work from different branches


================================================================================
EXAMPLE 5: VIEWING HISTORY
================================================================================

Scenario: Looking back at what was done

Commands:
---------
# See all commits in order
git log
# Output:
# commit abc123...
# Author: John Doe
# Date: June 20, 2026
# Message: Add color feature

# See shorter version
git log --oneline
# Output:
# abc123 Add color feature
# def456 Update greeting message
# ghi789 Add hello.txt file

# See changes in a specific commit
git show abc123
# Shows what changed in that commit

What They Learn:
----------------
Tracking project history and finding when changes were made


================================================================================
EXAMPLE 6: UNDOING MISTAKES
================================================================================

Scenario: "Oops, I made a mistake"

Commands:
---------
# Case 1: Undo changes before staging
git status
# modified: hello.txt
git restore hello.txt
# File goes back to last commit

# Case 2: Undo staging (before committing)
git add hello.txt
git restore --staged hello.txt
# File is unstaged but changes remain

# Case 3: Fix the last commit message
git commit -m "Wrnog message"
git commit --amend -m "Wrong message (corrected)"

What They Learn:
----------------
How to fix mistakes safely


================================================================================
QUICK TIPS FOR TEACHING THESE EXAMPLES
================================================================================

1. START WITH EXAMPLE 1
   - Let beginners create their first Git project
   - Build confidence before moving to complex concepts

2. USE ACTUAL FILE CHANGES
   - Don't just show terminal commands
   - Have them edit real files to see the impact

3. EMPHASIZE THE "WHY"
   - Explain what each command does
   - Explain why they need to do it

4. USE CONSISTENT NAMING
   - Branch names like "feature/feature-name" help understanding
   - Commit messages should be clear and descriptive

5. ENCOURAGE EXPERIMENTATION
   - Local Git is safe
   - Mistakes are learning opportunities

6. FOLLOW THE PROGRESSION
   - Example 1-3: Local Git basics
   - Example 4-5: Working with history and branches
   - Example 6: Safety and undo
   - Example 7-8: Remote repositories and real workflows


================================================================================
QUICK REFERENCE: GIT COMMANDS BY CATEGORY
================================================================================

SETUP & INITIALIZATION
  git init              - Initialize a new Git repository
  git clone <url>       - Download a project from GitHub

BASIC WORKFLOW
  git add <file>        - Stage file for commit
  git commit -m "msg"   - Save changes with a message
  git status            - See what changed

VIEWING & HISTORY
  git log               - See all commits
  git log --oneline     - Short commit history
  git show <commit>     - See changes in a commit
  git diff              - See unsaved changes

BRANCHES
  git branch            - List all branches
  git branch <name>     - Create new branch
  git checkout <branch> - Switch to a branch
  git merge <branch>    - Combine branches

UNDO & FIX
  git restore <file>    - Undo changes in a file
  git restore --staged  - Unstage a file
  git commit --amend    - Fix last commit message

REMOTE (GITHUB)
  git push origin <branch>  - Upload to GitHub
  git pull origin <branch>  - Download from GitHub
  git fetch                 - Get updates without merging


